text:
Broadway, east side, between Houston and Bleecker Street's, showing the Olympic Theatre at No. 624. This structure was opened on November 18, 1856 and soon afterward re-christened Laura Keene's New Theatre. This name was attached to half a dozen theatres during the period from 1850 to 1870. She retired in 1863, and John Duff, who then became the manager, re-opened the house as Mrs. John Woods Olympic Theatre. After Mrs. Woods retirement in 1866 it had a checkered career and was demolished in 1880. Joseph Jefferson appeared here in the play "Our American Cousin" on its first performance on October 18, 1858.

Betw. 1863-66

title: Manhattan: Broadway - Houston

text:
Broadway, north from but not including East Houston Street, showing horse drawn public coaches on Broadway, and a similarly drawn street car on Bleeker Street. The gas lamps shown in the foreground, at the curb, are in front of the Olympic Theatre, which is on the east side, between East Houston and Bleeker Streets.

Ewing Galloway

1865

Broadway, north across Houston Street, showing prominently the easterly side of this thoroughfare. Note the Olympic Theatre at No. 622. This was demolished about 1880. In the background, at the bend at 10th Street, is Grace P.E. Church.

Prior to 1880

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broadway, north from a point slightly south of Houston Street, showing vehicular and pedestrian traffic on this main artery of Manhattan during a spectacular period in the Citys history. Note the paved condition of the street bed and the lack of mechanical transportation; gas street lamps appearing midst overhead wire communications. The Grand Central Hotel which became the present Broadway Central Hotel is in the mid-distance with Grace P.E. Church farther northward, at the bend. The structures in the foreground, (both right and left sides) have disappeared today, vacant lots being thereon, caused by demolition work during construction of the Independent Subway. This photograph, made from one of the early dry plates, comes from a book entitled "How to make photographs" by T.C. Roche.

1883.

Broadway, west side, at West Houston Street, as viewed in a northward direction and showing prominently the Cable Building at the N.W. corner of both streets. The three buildings shown on the left are Nos. 605-607 (5-story Austin Building); No. 603, (8-story structure) and No. 601 (2-story structure). These were demolished in 1933 as a part of the Eighth Ave. Subway construction.

1-9 West Houston Street and 605-609 Broadway, at the S.W. corner, a brick office building faced with iron. It probably dates from the 1870's.

September 19, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

W. Houston Street, south side, at and east across Broadway. 13-11 West Houston Street, adjoining the building at the S.W. corner, is being demolished. No. 9-1, the corner building, will shortly follow.

The bend in Houston Street at Broadway -- West Houston Street joins Broadway at right angles, but East Houston does not -- is really the meeting place of the original Houston Street and of North Street, after the letter was extended west from the Bowery. Houston Street absorbed North Street in 1833, and the whole was renumbered west from the East River. The division of Houston Street into East and West did not come until after the absorption of Hammersley Street in 1858.

Broadway, west side, at West Houston Street, showing a clearance at the S.W. corner of same, which was occupied by 2 buildings, Nos. 609-605 and 603 Broadway. Remaining is the 12-story Ayer Building (left) No. 599, which was adjoining the demolished structures. On the right appears a part of the Cable Building, No. 611-621 Broadway, a 9-story structure at the N.W. corner. This view is photographed in a southwestward direction from Crosby Street and shows clearances in the foreground on both sides of East Houston Street.
